frameDefinitions: An Entity is rated as unexpected for its context in terms of its magnitude.
This frame has to do with people (the Residents) residing in Locations, sometimes with a Co-resident.
An Entity has existed for a length of time, the Age.
A Speaker states or makes known a future Eventuality on the basis of some Evidence.
An entity goes through several versions, from initial to final.
An Entity is presented as having been seen or experienced by a (typically generic and backgrounded)
frameExamples: The <t>entire</t> apple was riddled with worms .
This building is twenty thousand years <t>old</t>.
The Weather Centre <t>predicted</t> that it would be warmer but wet for the weekend.
Susanna Fulton's work is <t>new</t> to me.
listRoleDefinitions: The item which is described in terms of its expectedness in the context.
The individual(s) that reside at the <fen>Location</fen>.
The place in which somebody resides.
A person or group of people that the resident is staying with or among.
This role refers to the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Resident</fen> resides.
The <fen>Entity</fen> for which a particular age is under consideration.
The feature of an <fen>Entity</fen> which is a function of the amount of time that the <fen>Entity</fen> has existed.
A quantity or other characterization of the <fen>Entity</fen>'s age.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Age</fen> from the norm.
The Frame Element <fen>Expressor</fen> marks expressions that indicate a body part, gesture or other expression of the <fen>Entity</fen> that reflect its age.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Entity</fen> is at a particular <fen>Age</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> makes a prediction.

This role marks expressions that indicate an event or state that is predicted to occur or hold at a future time. A single <fen>Eventuality</fen> may be expressed discontinuously in a raising construction. This role is also used for expressions that denote entities with variable attributes about which the <fen>Speaker</fen> makes predictions.
The <fen>Medium</fen> is the physical entity or channel used by the <fen>Speaker</fen> to transmit the prediction.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the prediction pertains. It is normally expressed as a PP Complement headed by <m>about</m>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the prediction is made.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Speaker</fen> makes the prediction.
The <fen>Item</fen> is one version among several versions (which may or may not yet exist), progressively getting closer to a final version.
A concrete thing or abstract phenomenon or fact that is assessed in terms of how well recognizable it is to a <fen>Cognizer</fen>.
The (typically non-specific and backgrounded) sentient being for whom the <fen>Entity</fen> possesses a specified level of recognizability.
The deviation of the actual level of recognizability of the <fen>Entity</fen> from the level specified by the target.
listRoleExamples: The entire <fex>day</fex> was spent on the project .
'Who's there?' she barked. 'Ensign Kim, ma'me,' the youngish voice of Voyager's young Harry Kim came over the comm line. '
<fex>The institute</fex> forecast an increase in leisure spending of 15 per cent.
The events that would occur over the next several years had been predicted <fex>in the Bible</fex>.
John predicted <fex>last year</fex> that he would be finished by October.
Greenman predicted <fex>at a small dinner party</fex> that the market would rise again.
He gave <fex>an address</fex> quite familiar to the chauffeur.
The information used to illustrate the concept is familiar <fex>to the reader</fex>.
He gave an address <fex>quite</fex> familiar to the chauffeur.
